<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Student Tutors Youths, Overcomes Disability to Earn Congressional Award</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Chad Binette
		
		<span class="date">June 10, 2008</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: 345px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1469/en_US/tutordisability.jpg" height="226" width="345"  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Jacque Brund</p>
			
			<p>James Martin, who earned the Congressional Award, and Linda Martin, James' mom and the classroom teacher of many pupils whom James tutored.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004122b12132011a72d4f80004cc2">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
							
								<h3>Story Images</h3>
								<ul id="story_images">
							
						<li>
						<a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004122b12132011a72d4f80004cc2&amp;img_mode=1&amp;index=0">
							<img width="100" alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/1000/NE1469/en_US/secondaryCHAD.jpg"  />
						</a>
						</li>
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			</ul><p  class="note">Click thumbnails for full-size images.</p>
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:jdmartin.ucf@gmail.com ">James Martin</a></h4>
			
			
			
			
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cbinette@mail.ucf.edu">Chad Binette, UCF News and Information</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6312</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:williamson@congressionalaward.org">Eliot Williamson, Congressional Award</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>202-226-0130</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.congressionalaward.org">Congressional Award</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>As a Lake County high school student, James Martin tutored community college students in science and math. To play basketball and football, he had to overcome a disability that made it difficult for him to walk.</p>
<p>Now a Physics major at the University of Central Florida, Martin also earned enough college credits in high school through dual-enrollment courses to receive his associate's degree from Lake-Sumter Community College before his South Lake High School diploma.</p>
<p>Martin's accomplishments helped him achieve the Congressional Award Gold Medal, the top national honor bestowed by Congress recognizing the service and achievements of youths ages 14 to 23. Less than one percent of youth who initiate the process of earning a Congressional Award will qualify for the Gold Medal.</p>
<p>Martin, 18, of Groveland, will be honored June 19 at a ceremony on Capitol Hill and a reception at the Ronald Reagan Building and International Trade Center. He will be joined by his sponsor, U.S. Rep. Ginny Brown-Waite, R-Brooksville, at the ceremony featuring U.S. House and Senate leaders.</p>
<p>As a South Lake High School student, Martin offered after-school tutoring in math and science almost daily to Clermont Middle School students. He also tutored Lake-Sumter Community College students in the same subjects.</p>
<p>&quot;He's always been the kind of person who thinks of others,&quot; said Linda Martin, James' mother and the special education teacher of many of the Clermont Middle students whom her son tutored. &quot;He has made a difference in so many people's lives.&quot;</p>
<p>The Congressional Award's physical fitness requirement was the most challenging for Martin, who endured 18 months of physical therapy and surgery on both of his legs to lengthen his Achilles tendons. He played junior varsity football at South Lake High for about six weeks and basketball on a local youth team for eight seasons.</p>
<p>While studying at UCF in the summer, Martin is taking advantage of the research opportunities on campus. He is participating in the university's Research Experience for Undergraduates program in Lasers, Optics and Optical Materials.</p>
<p>Collaborating with Martin Richardson, a professor in the College of Optics and Photonics and director of UCF's Townes Laser Institute, James Martin is working with telescopes and how to ensure that light collected by the telescopes is properly read by computers. He plans to study in France next summer as part of the same research program.</p>
<p>&quot;I felt I needed to go on to my next challenge,&quot; Martin said. &quot;I really wanted to get into a research project that would provide me with the opportunity to accelerate my career.&quot;</p>
<p>Martin chose to attend UCF because of the strength of its Physics program and the presence of the Robinson Observatory on campus. As an Astronomy Society member, he volunteers at public viewings in the observatory.</p>
<p>Established by Congress in 1979, the Congressional Award program encourages young people to set and achieve challenging goals that build character and foster community service, personal development and citizenship. The program receives no federal funding and relies on charitable contributions.</p>
<p>Recipients achieve bronze and silver medals before winning the gold medal. U.S. Rep. Ginny Brown-Waite, R-5th District, presented Martin with his bronze and silver medals in 2006.</p>
<p>&quot;This prestigious award's requirements are so tough that few young Americans even consider attempting to earn the bronze award, let alone the gold,&quot; she said. &quot;As a testament to the dedication and commitment it takes to earn the Congressional Award Gold Medal, James started toward this goal when he was thirteen, and has worked nonstop since then to ensure he one day achieved this great honor.&nbsp; I am extremely proud of James for what he has been able to accomplish and look forward to welcoming him to Washington, D.C., to receive his Gold Medal.&quot;</p>
<p>To qualify for the Congressional Award Gold Medal, Martin was required to log more than 400 hours of community service - a number that he greatly exceeded, along with 200 hours of physical fitness activities, 200 hours of personal development activities and an exploration activity with a stay of at least four consecutive nights.</p>
<p>For personal development, Martin took four years of French courses and read for thousands of hours. He traveled to Washington, D.C., and toured the White House, Capitol and a few museums to fulfill the exploration requirement.</p>
<p>Visit <a href="http://www.congressionalaward.org">www.congressionalaward.org</a> for more information on the Congressional Award program.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity: </strong><span style="font-weight: normal;">The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 5th largest in the nation with more than 48,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</span></p>
		
	
